  "text": "In the 1950s, the island began to plant large areas of rubber trees to meet China's national defense and economic needs. It is the second largest natural rubber production base in China, with an area of 5.4 × 10 5 ha in 2015 [25] . According to Hainan Island National Land Cover Dataset in 2010 [CITATION_1] , forest (include rubber plantations), cropland, grassland, water, and built-up account for 63.4%, 25.7%, 3.3%, 3.8%, and 3.6% of the total land area, respectively.",
